The Duplicated Index Issue¶

When we concatenate the dfs , we get duplicate Indexes .

Since each df is carrying their 0 base range index , its not discarded.

In [62]:
#To check duplicate indexes
#schools.index.duplicated()

If there are duplicate Indexes , pandas cannot make use of a non-unique label and label based indexing will not work

  • schools.loc[0 : 2] ===> will give Error
In [63]:
#One fix is reset_index()  and set the drop parameter to True
#schools.reset_index(drop = True , inplace = True)
In [65]:
#Now if we check the duplicated index 
#It gives 0 , that means it shows that the Index is unique now
schools.index.duplicated().sum()
Out[65]:
0

Enforcing Unique Indices¶

In [67]:
#reset index ==> df.reset_index(drop = True) OR pd.concat(ignore_index = True)

These options might be inadequate for some cases . In certain cases , the index from the original Dataframe is meaningful , we want to preserve it at the same time we want it to be unique

  • here there are no duplicates because none of the schools exist in both

The append() method : A Special case of concat()¶

We use append() method to add rows to our existing datasets

  • you might have noticed that append() and concat() are actually quite similar
  • For a brief review , if you want to add the Liberal art schools to the party schools
  • we appended all the rows fom party to liberal df

  • We end up getting same dataframe in both cases : (append and concat)
  • Then what is the difference?
  • In this particular use case , the two methods are identical
  • But in other context there are differences in how they behave
  • Notice that the append() method can only be called on existing dfs or Series
  • liberal.append(party)
  • append() only operates along the Index axis (axis =0)
  • Concat() is a lot more flexible : concat along Index axis as well as the column axis
  • so you cam think of append() as a special case of concat() where the axis has been fixed to 0

  • so far we have been working with similar structured dfs
  • But most often its not the case
  • A df couls have an extra column that we don't really need

The MERGE() method¶

In [212]:
#merge() is similar to SQL

- merge() in pandas gives us the flexibility to join various Dataframes and Series objects¶

How joining or merging is different from concatenation or appending¶

Concat doesn't care about the df content

merge() flexibly combines multiple datasets on the basis of the content that they have

Inner and Outer Joins¶

What logic should be applied when we merge the two datasets?

  • Inner join is the Default
  • Inner Join only returns the records that are present in both Right and Left object

Left VS Right Joins¶

merge() method also supports two other join methods

  • left join
  • right join

left join indicates we want to preserve all columns from left dataframe¶

In [258]:
#we are merging the dfs on 'School Name'

One - to - One and One - to - Many Joins¶

When working with data in general .Specially when combining multiple Datasets and Tables.Sooner or later we are going to come across terminology that describes the type of association between different entities in our data.

One to One¶

A One-to-One join happens when each record in a DataFrame with one Record in another dataset.

  • If we look at 'ivy' dataset , we see a list of 8 unique Universities (refer to column : 'School Name')

But , now the question is "Is this a One - to - One" JOIN ?¶

How can we determine whether each 'Ivy League' School ('School Type') is associated with one and only one record in the "regions" dataframe

The answer comes down to whether the two datasets bith have unique values in the resulting "Key" column That is "School Name" here.

  • We get exactly the 8 ivy league schools
  • So we confirmed that both datasets have unique values on the key column for the keys that they have in common .
  • Therefore the type of join between 'ivy' and 'regions' is a One-To-One join

Many - To - Many Joins¶

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/19177934#questions/13647656

These are the types of joins that occur when we have Duplicates in the key columns from both the left and the right objects that are being merged.

  • Suppose we conduct a Survey
  • What is the prestige of an ivy or engg degree?
  • And from that survey we collected data that looked like this:

This type of behaviour where it multiplies is called the Cartesian product

  • This arises when there are duplicated values on the 'Key' columns for both objects being merged.

Summary:¶

Join Cardinalities:

To differentiate between One-To-One ; One-To-Many and Many-To-Many, we simply look for repeating values in the respective Key columns that the Key values that the two merged objects have in common.

  • One - To - One : [Dual Sided Uniques] : Both merge objects contain unique values in respective Key
  • One - To - Many : [One Sided Uniques] : One of the merge objects contain Non-unique values
  • Many - To - Many : [One Sided Non - Uniques] : Both merge objects contain Non-unique values

Merging by Index¶

Above we saw , Pandas utilizes a common column as a Key column for the merge

  • We also use the "on" parameter to explicitly specify the column
  • We explored the "left-on" and "right-on" parameters to pass different "key" columns from the right and left objects
  • In all these we performed join operations using plain dataframe columns
  • Occassionally , we might be interested in joining by index instead
  • Fortunately , the Pandas merge() method fully supports that
